Load balancing means:
Distributing workload or client requests among multiple servers evenly.
Preventing one server from becoming overloaded.


Suppose:
Many clients send requests.
There are multiple servers available.
Instead of sending all requests to one server:
Requests are distributed among different servers.

This improves:
Performance
Speed
Reliability


Real-Life Example

Think of:
Supermarket Billing Counters
If all customers go to one counter:
Huge queue forms.
So customers are distributed across:
Counter 1
Counter 2
Counter 3
This is load balancing.



Common Load Balancing Algorithms:
1. Round Robin Algorithm: Requests are distributed one-by-one sequentially.
2. Least Connections Algorithm: Request goes to server with minimum active connections.
3. Random Algorithm: Server selected randomly.
4. Weighted Round Robin: More powerful servers get more requests.




STEPS:
1.Clients generate requests.
2. Load balancer receives all requests.
3.Algorithm decides target server.
Example:
Round Robin
Least Connection
4.Selected server processes request.
5.Response returned to client.
